<p><br/>
<a name="Burial of the Dead"></a> </p>
<div><center>
<table>
<tr>
<td><a href="http://town.hall.org/Archives/radio/IMS/HarperAudio/011894_harp_01_ITH.ram"><font><img alt="Eliot reading The Waste Land - (c) HarperCollins Audio - RealAdio format" src="../images/speaker.gif"/></font></a><font> I. </font><a href="burial_N.htm"><font>The
        Burial of the Dead</font></a> <p>\xA0 April is the
        cruellest month, breeding\xA0 <br/>
        Lilacs out of the dead land, mixing\xA0 <br/>
        Memory and desire, stirring\xA0 <br/>
        Dull roots with spring rain.\xA0 <br/>
        Winter kept us warm, covering\xA0 <br/>
        Earth in forgetful snow, feeding\xA0 <br/>
        A little life with dried tubers.\xA0 <br/>
        Summer surprised us, coming over the <a href="Stanbergersee_N.htm">Starnbergersee</a>\xA0<a href="summer_N.htm"><img alt="Marie Larisch" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        With a shower of rain; we stopped in the colonnade,\xA0
        <br/>
        And went on in sunlight, into the <a href="hofgarten_N.htm">Hofgarten</a>,\xA0 <br/>
        And drank coffee, and talked for an hour.\xA0 <br/>
        Bin gar keine Russin, stamm' aus Litauen, echt deutsch. <a href="ichbin_N.htm"><img alt="click here for translation" src="../images/T.gif"/></a><br/>
        And when we were children, staying at the archduke's,\xA0
        <br/>
        My cousin's, he took me out on a sled,\xA0 <br/>
        And I was frightened. He said, Marie,\xA0 <br/>
        Marie, hold on tight. And down we went.\xA0 <br/>
        In the mountains, there you feel free.\xA0<a href="mountains_N.htm"><img alt="Marie Larisch" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        I read, much of the night, and go south in the winter. <br/>
<br/>
        \xA0 What are the roots that clutch, what branches grow\xA0
        <br/>
        Out if this stony rubbish? <a href="sonofman_N.htm">Son
        of man</a>,\xA0 <br/>
        You cannot say, or guess, for you know only\xA0 <br/>
        A heap of broken images, where the sun beats,\xA0 <br/>
        And the dead tree gives no shelter, the cricket no relief,\xA0<a href="deadtree_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. Ecclesiastes XII, v. [Eliot's note] " src="../images/R.gif"/></a><br/>
        And the dry stone no sound of water. Only\xA0 <br/>
        There is shadow under this red rock,\xA0<a href="Thereisshad_N.htm"><img alt="Bible imagery" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        (Come in under the shadow of this red rock),\xA0 <br/>
        And I will show you something different from either\xA0
        <br/>
        Your shadow at morning striding behind you\xA0 <br/>
        Or your shadow at evening rising to meet you;\xA0 <br/>
        I will show you fear in a handful of dust.\xA0 </p>
<blockquote>
<p><i>Frish weht der Wind\xA0</i> <br/>
<i>Der Heimat zu\xA0</i> <br/>
<i>Mein Irisch Kind,\xA0</i> <br/>
<i>Wo weilest du?</i> <a href="Wagner5-8_T.htm"><img alt="click here for translation" src="../images/T.gif"/></a> <a href="Wagner_3.htm"><img alt="V. Tristan und Isolde, I, verses 5-8. [Eliot's note] " src="../images/R.gif"/></a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>"You gave me hyacinths first a year ago;\xA0 <br/>
        They called me the hyacinth girl." <br/>
        --Yet when we came back, late, from the Hyacinth garden,\xA0
        <br/>
        Your arms full, and your hair wet, I could not\xA0 <br/>
        Speak, and my eyes failed, I was neither\xA0 <br/>
        Living nor dead, and I knew nothing,\xA0 <br/>
        Looking into the heart of light, the silence.\xA0 <br/>
<i>Oed' und leer das Meer.</i> <a href="Wagner3-24_T.htm"><img alt="click here for translation" src="../images/T.gif"/></a> <a href="Wagner_3.htm"><img alt="Cf. Tristan und Isolde, III, verse 24 [Eliot's note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
<br/>
        \xA0 Madame <a href="Sosostri_N.htm">Sosostris</a>,
        famous clairvoyante,\xA0 <br/>
        Had a bad cold, nevertheless\xA0 <br/>
        Is known to be the wisest woman in Europe,\xA0 <br/>
        With a wicked <a href="packof_N.htm">pack of cards</a>.
        Here, said she,\xA0 <br/>
        Is your card, the drowned <a href="phoenici_N.htm">Phoenician
        Sailor</a>,\xA0 <br/>
        (Those are pearls that were his eyes. Look!)\xA0<a href="Tempest1-2-487_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. The Tempest, 2.1.398" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        Here is <a href="Belladonna_N.htm">Belladonna</a>, the <a href="ladyofro_N.htm">Lady of the Rocks</a>,\xA0 <br/>
        The lady of situations.\xA0 <br/>
        Here is the <a href="threestaves_N.htm">man with three
        staves</a>, and here the <a href="wheel_N.htm">Wheel</a>,\xA0
        <br/>
        And here is the <a href="oneeye_N.htm">one-eyed merchant</a>,
        and this card,\xA0 <br/>
        Which is blank, is something he carries on his back,\xA0
        <br/>
        Which I am forbidden to see. I do not find\xA0 <br/>
<a href="hanged_N.htm">The Hanged Man</a>. Fear death by
        water.\xA0 <br/>
        I see crowds of people, walking round in a ring,\xA0 <br/>
        Thank you. If you see dear Mrs. Equitone,\xA0 <br/>
        Tell her I bring the horoscope myself:\xA0 <br/>
        One must be so careful these days. <br/>
<br/>
        \xA0 Unreal City,\xA0<a href="unreal_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. Baudelaire: 'Fourmillante citĂ©, citĂ© pleine de rĂŞves, OĂą le spectre en plein jour raccroche le passant' [Eliot's Note'" src="../images/R.gif"/></a><br/>
        Under the brown fog of a winter dawn,\xA0 <br/>
        A crowd flowed over London Bridge, so many,\xA0<a href="Ihadnot_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. Inferno III, 55-57 [Eliot's Note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        I had not thought death had undone so many.\xA0<a href="sighs_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. Inferno IV, 25-27 [Eliot's Note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a><br/>
        Sighs, short and infrequent, were exhaled,\xA0 <br/>
        And each man fixed his eyes before his feet.\xA0 <br/>
        Flowed up the hill and down King William Street,\xA0 <br/>
        To where <a href="saintmar_N.htm">Saint Mary Woolnoth</a>
        kept the hours\xA0 <br/>
        With a <a href="deadsoun_N.htm">dead sound </a>on the
        final stroke of nine.\xA0 <br/>
        There I saw one I knew, and stopped him, crying: "Stetson!\xA0
        <br/>
        You who were with me in the ships at <a href="mylae_N.htm">Mylae</a>!\xA0 <br/>
        '<a href="thatcorp_N.htm">That corpse</a> you planted
        last year in your garden,\xA0 <br/>
        'Has it begun to sprout? Will it bloom this year?\xA0 <br/>
        'Or has the sudden frost disturbed its bed?\xA0 <br/>
        O keep the Dog far hence, that's friend to men,\xA0<a href="keepthedog_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. the Dirge in Webster's White Devil. [Eliot's note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        'Or with his nails he'll dig it up again!\xA0 <br/>
        'You! Hypocrite lecteur!---mon semblable,--mon frere!'\xA0<a href="hypocrit_T.htm"><img alt="click here for translation" src="../images/T.gif"/></a> <a href="youhypocrite_N.htm"><img alt="V. Baudelaire, Preface to Fleurs du Mal. [Eliot's note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> </p>
</td>
