<p><a name="Game of Chess"></a></p>
<div><center>
<table>
<tr>
<td><a href="http://town.hall.org/Archives/radio/IMS/HarperAudio/011894_harp_02_ITH.au"><font><img alt="Eliot reading The Waste Land - (c) HarperCollins Audio - RealAdio format" src="../images/speaker.gif"/></font></a><font> II. </font><a href="agameof_N.htm"><font>A Game of Chess</font></a><font>\xA0</font>
<p>The Chair she sat in, like a burnished throne,\xA0 <a href="chair_N.htm"><img alt=" 77. Cf. Antony and Cleopatra, II, ii, l. 190 [Eliot's Note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a><br/>
        Glowed on the marble, where the glass\xA0 <br/>
        Held up by standards wrought with fruited vines\xA0 <br/>
        From which a golden Cupidon peeped out\xA0 <br/>
        (Another hid his eyes behind his wing)\xA0 <br/>
        Doubled the flames of sevenbranched candelabra\xA0 <br/>
        Reflecting light upon the table as\xA0 <br/>
        The glitter of her jewels rose to meet it,\xA0 <br/>
        From satin cases poured in rich profusion.\xA0 <br/>
        In vials of ivory and colored glass\xA0 <br/>
        Unstoppered, lurked her strange synthetic perfumes,\xA0
        <br/>
        Unguent, powdered, or liquid--troubled, confused\xA0 <br/>
        And drowned the sense in odors; stirred by the air\xA0 <br/>
        That freshened from the window, these ascended\xA0 <br/>
        In flattening the prolonged candle flames,\xA0 <br/>
        Flung their smoke into the laquearia,\xA0<a href="flung_N.htm"><img alt="Laquearia. V. Aeneid, I, 726: dependent lychni laqueribus auries incensi, et noctem flammis funalia vincunt [Eliot's note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        Stirring the pattern on the coffered ceiling.\xA0 <br/>
        Huge sea-wood fed with copper\xA0 <br/>
        Burned green and orange, framed by the colored stone,\xA0
        <br/>
        In which sad light a carved dolphin swam.\xA0 <br/>
        Above the antique mantel was displayed\xA0 <br/>
        As though a window gave upon the sylvan scene\xA0<a href="sylvan_N.htm"><img alt="Sylvan scene. V. Milton, Paradise Lost, IV, 140. [Eliot's note] " src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        The change of Philomel, by the barbarous king\xA0<a href="philomel_N.htm"><img alt="V. Ovid, Metamorphoses, VI, Philomela. [Eliot's note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        So rudely forced; yet there the nightingale\xA0<a href="rudely_N.htm"><img src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        Filled all the desert with inviolable voice\xA0 <br/>
        And still she cried, and still the world pursues,\xA0 <br/>
        "Jug Jug" to dirty ears. <a href="jugjug_N.htm"><img src="../images/R.gif"/></a><br/>
        And other withered stumps of time\xA0 <br/>
        Were told upon the walls; staring forms\xA0 <br/>
        Leaned out, leaning, hushing the room enclosed.\xA0 <br/>
        Footsteps shuffled on the stair.\xA0 <br/>
        Under the firelight, under the brush, her hair\xA0 <br/>
        Spread out in fiery points\xA0 <br/>
        Glowed into words, then would be savagely still. <br/>
<br/>
        \xA0 "My nerves are bad tonight. Yes, bad. Stay
        with me.\xA0 <br/>
        \xA0 Speak to me. Why do you never speak. Speak.\xA0 <br/>
        \xA0\xA0\xA0 What are you thinking of? What
        thinking? What?\xA0 <br/>
        \xA0 I never know what you are thinking. Think." <br/>
<br/>
        \xA0 I think we are in rats' alley\xA0<a href="ratsalle_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. Part III, l. 204 [Eliot's note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        Where the dead men lost their bones. <br/>
<br/>
        "What is that noise?"\xA0 <br/>
        \xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0
        The wind under the door. <a href="windunde_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. Webster: 'Is the wind in that door still?' [Eliot's note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a><br/>
        "What is that noise now? What is the wind doing?"\xA0
        <br/>
        \xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0
        Nothing again nothing.\xA0 <br/>
<br/>
        \xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0
        "Do\xA0 <br/>
        You know nothing? Do you see nothing? Do you remember\xA0
        <br/>
        Nothing?" <br/>
<br/>
        \xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 I remember\xA0 <br/>
        Those are pearls that were his eyes.\xA0<a href="pearls_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. Part I, l. 37,48. [Eliot's note] " src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        "Are you alive, or not? Is there nothing in your
        head?"\xA0 <br/>
        \xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0
        But\xA0 <br/>
        O O O O that Shakespeherian Rag---\xA0 <a href="shakespehe_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. Part I, l. 37,48. [Eliot's note] " src="../images/R.gif"/></a><br/>
        It's so elegant\xA0 <br/>
        So intelligent\xA0 <br/>
        "What shall I do now? What shall I do? <br/>
        I shall rush out as I am, and walk the street\xA0 <br/>
        With my hair down, so. What shall we do tomorrow?\xA0 <br/>
        What shall we ever do?"\xA0 <br/>
        \xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0
        The hot water at ten.\xA0 <br/>
        And if it rains, a closed car at four.\xA0 <br/>
        And we shall play a game of chess,\xA0<a href="weshallplay_N.htm"><img alt="Cf. the game of chess in Middleton's Women beware Women. [Eliot's note]" src="../images/R.gif"/></a> <br/>
        Pressing lidless eyes and waiting for a knock upon the
        door. <br/>
<br/>
        \xA0 When Lil's husband got <a href="demobbed_W.htm">demobbed</a>,
        I said--\xA0 <br/>
        I didn't mince my words, I said to her myself,\xA0 <br/>
<b>Hurry up please it's time</b> <a href="hurryup_N.htm"><img alt="Traditional closing call of British bartender at closing time" src="../images/R.gif"/></a><br/>
        Now Albert's coming back, make yourself a bit smart.\xA0
        <br/>
        He'll want to know what you done with that money he gave
        you\xA0 <br/>
        To get yourself some teeth. He did, I was there.\xA0 <br/>
        You have them all out, Lil, and get a nice set,\xA0 <br/>
        He said, I swear, I can't bear to look at you.\xA0 <br/>
        And no more can't I, I said, and think of poor Albert,\xA0
        <br/>
        He's been in the army four years, he wants a good time,\xA0
        <br/>
        And if you don't give it him, there's others will, I said.\xA0
        <br/>
        Oh is there, she said. Something o' that, I said.\xA0 <br/>
        Then I'll know who to thank, she said, and give me a
        straight look.\xA0 <br/>
<b>Hurry up please it's time</b> <br/>
        If you don't like it you can get on with it, I said.\xA0
        <br/>
        Others can pick and choose if you can't.\xA0 <br/>
        But if Albert makes off, it won't be for lack of telling.\xA0
        <br/>
        You ought to be ashamed, I said, to look so antique.\xA0
        <br/>
        (And her only thirty-one.)\xA0 <br/>
        I can't help it, she said, pulling a long face,\xA0 <br/>
        It's them pills I took, <a href="tobring_W.htm">to bring
        it off</a>, she said.\xA0 <br/>
        (She's had five already, and nearly died of young George.)\xA0
        <br/>
        The chemist said it would be all right, but I've never
        been the same.\xA0 <br/>
        You <i>are </i>a proper fool, I said.\xA0 <br/>
        Well, if Albert won't leave you alone, there it is, I
        said,\xA0 <br/>
        What you get married for if you don't want children?\xA0
        <br/>
<b>Hurry up please, it's time\xA0</b> <br/>
        Well, that Sunday Albert was home, they had a hot <a href="gammon_N.htm">gammon</a>,\xA0 <br/>
        And they asked me in to dinner, to get the beauty of it
        hot--\xA0 <br/>
<b>Hurry up please it's time\xA0</b> <br/>
<b>Hurry up please it's time\xA0</b> <br/>
        Goonight Bill. Goonight Lou. Goonight May. Goonight.\xA0
        <br/>
        Ta ta. Goonight. Goonight.\xA0 <br/>
        Good night, ladies, good night, sweet ladies, good night,
        good night. <a href="goodnigh_N.htm"><img alt="Cf the mad Ophelia's departing words from Hamlet, 4.5.72. Ophelia too met death by water..." src="../images/R.gif"/></a></p>
</td>
